The paper discusses the design and implementation of an augmented version of conventional SRAM bit-cells for in-memory Boolean computations. This topic falls under the broad category of computer architecture and design, which is covered by several arXiv CS sub-categories. 

cs.AR (Architecture) is the most likely sub-category as it specifically deals with the design and organization of computer systems, including memory hierarchies and processor architectures. 

cs.ET (Emerging Technologies) is also a likely sub-category as the paper proposes a novel approach to improving the energy-efficiency and throughput of computing systems, which is a key focus of emerging technologies research. 

cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) is another possible sub-category as the paper discusses the potential benefits of in-memory computing for data-intensive applications such as machine learning, which often require distributed and parallel computing architectures. 

cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science) is a possible sub-category as the paper presents a case study of implementing the advanced encryption standard algorithm using the proposed in-memory computing techniques, which is relevant to computational security and finance. 

cs.SE (Software Engineering) is a less likely sub-category as the paper does not focus on software development or programming techniques, but rather on hardware design and implementation.
